-- South Africa Increases Coal Exports to India by 74% in July, Trader Says
-- Dinakar Sethuraman
-- 2010-08-06T09:15:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-08-06/south-africa-s-richards-bay-boosts-india-coal-exports-by-74-traders-say.html

          
          
             South Africa’s Richards Bay, the
continent’s largest coal terminal, increased sales to India by
74 percent in July from June, according to a trader.  
 Purchases rose to 2.1 million metric tons, according to a
note yesterday by mjunction Services Ltd., a web-based trader
backed by India’s biggest steel producers. Purchases climbed 52
percent from a year earlier. Imports in the first seven months
rose 14 percent to 11.63 million tons.  
 The nation’s thermal coal imports may climb to 72 million
tons in 2011, according to Tata Power Co., which is setting up a
coal-fired power plant with a capacity of 4,000 megawatts. The
International Monetary Fund revised India’s 2010 economic growth
forecast to 9.4 percent from its earlier prediction of 8.8
percent in April.  
 The power sector in India may face a coal shortage of 52.43
million tons in the year ending March 2011, mjunction said.
citing India’s Coal Minister Sriprakash Jaiswal. The country’s
demand for the fuel may be about 656 million tons this fiscal
year, with users facing a shortage of about 83 million tons of
the thermal and steel-making varieties.  
 Pakistani purchases from Richards Bay more than doubled to
182,624 tons in July from June, according to mjunction. Imports
rose 44 percent in July from a year earlier.  
 Richards Bay increased shipments by almost 50 percent in
July from June after a strike at Transnet Ltd. disrupted rail
and port services the previous month.  
